seo.description.default = Help map and assess sidewalks in {0} through virtual exploration. Open data on curb ramps, obstacles, and surface problems for a more accessible world.
seo.description.landing = Help find sidewalk safety and accessibility issues in {0} from your laptop. Your labels help researchers, cities, and communities improve their sidewalks.
seo.description.explore = Virtually walk the streets of {0} and label curb ramps, missing sidewalks, obstacles, and surface problems to improve accessibility.
seo.description.validate = Review sidewalk accessibility labels placed by others in {0} and help improve data quality.
seo.description.gallery = Browse street-level images of sidewalk accessibility features and barriers found in {0}.
seo.description.label.map = Interactive map of every sidewalk accessibility label in {0}: curb ramps, obstacles, surface problems, and more.
seo.description.help = Learn how to use Project Sidewalk: labeling how-tos, accuracy tips, and frequently asked questions.
seo.description.cities = Project Sidewalk is deployed in cities around the world. See every deployment city or bring Project Sidewalk to yours.
seo.description.api = Free and open sidewalk accessibility data for {0}: raw labels, label clusters, streets, and Access Scores in JSON, CSV, GeoJSON, GeoPackage, and Shapefile formats.
seo.description.about = Learn about Project Sidewalk: our mission to map the world''s sidewalks, the research team behind it, and the open data it produces.
seo.og.image.alt = Screenshot of Project Sidewalk''s virtual street-view exploration with accessibility labels placed along a sidewalk.

# About page (#4237, redesigned in #4631). Static copy is server-rendered and doubles as the no-JS/crawler fallback;
# numbers in data-live-stat spans are hydrated from /v3/api/aggregateStats (aggregateStats.js), and the team,
# publications, and funders sections are hydrated from the Makeability Lab API (aboutPage.js).
about.title = About Project Sidewalk
about.hero.title = We''re mapping and assessing <span class="about-hero-accent">every sidewalk</span> in the world.
about.hero.subtitle = Project Sidewalk is an open-source research project that combines crowdsourcing and AI to map and assess city sidewalks — and opens every data point to researchers, governments, and communities.
about.hero.attribution = An academic research project led by Professor Jon E. Froehlich (University of Washington) and Professor Yochai Eisenberg (University of Illinois Chicago).
about.hero.cta.explore = Start exploring
about.hero.cta.data = Get the data
about.stats.heading = Project Sidewalk by the numbers
about.stats.km = Kilometers explored
about.stats.labels = Labels
about.stats.validations = Validations
about.stats.cities = Cities
about.stats.countries = Countries
about.how.title = How it works
about.how.intro = We aim to map and assess every sidewalk in the world using remote crowdsourcing, artificial intelligence, and online street-level imagery. Anyone with a web browser can help — no special tools required.
about.how.step.explore.title = Explore &amp; label
about.how.step.explore.body = Volunteers virtually walk city streets in a game-like web tool, labeling curb ramps, missing sidewalks, obstacles, and surface problems in street-level imagery.
about.how.step.validate.title = Validate
about.how.step.validate.body = Contributors then review each other''s labels — assisted by AI — agreeing or disagreeing with what they see, so the dataset stays accurate and trustworthy.
about.how.step.data.title = Open data
about.how.step.data.body = Every label feeds an open dataset that researchers, governments, and community advocates use to understand and improve sidewalk accessibility.
about.how.cta = <a href="/explore">Start exploring</a> or <a href="/validate">validate labels</a> to contribute.
about.impact.title = How Project Sidewalk makes impact
about.impact.intro = The goal isn''t just data — it''s making cities more walkable, rollable, and safe for pedestrians. Here are a few of the ways communities, governments, and schools have put Project Sidewalk to work.
about.impact.chicago.place = Chicago, Illinois
about.impact.chicago.body = Aldermanic wards have used resident-collected Project Sidewalk data to prioritize sidewalk improvement funds more equitably, and our team advised the city''s Pedestrian Safety Committee on moving beyond complaint-driven repairs.
about.impact.illinois.place = Lincolnwood, Roselle &amp; Mendota, Illinois
about.impact.illinois.body = Project Sidewalk data helped shape ADA Transition Plans for Lincolnwood and Roselle, and community partners in Mendota used it to win a Safe Routes to School grant for safer paths to school.
about.impact.burnaby.place = Burnaby, Canada
about.impact.burnaby.body = The City of Burnaby integrated Project Sidewalk data into the prioritization framework for its New Sidewalks Program and its recently adopted Accessibility Strategy.
about.impact.newberg.place = Newberg, Oregon
about.impact.newberg.body = After residents mapped local sidewalks, the city council created a new sidewalk renovation program — including $50,000 for immediate repairs and grants to help homeowners fix the sidewalks outside their homes.
about.impact.zurich.place = Zurich, Switzerland
about.impact.zurich.body = Zurich publishes Project Sidewalk data in the city''s open data portal, and the deployment won a Smart City Hub Switzerland Award in the citizen-science category.
about.impact.schools.place = Classrooms across the U.S.
about.impact.schools.body = Students use Project Sidewalk to learn data science and civic advocacy — from Girl Scouts in Oradell, New Jersey presenting findings to their city council, to <a href="https://makeabilitylab.cs.washington.edu/news/mcdevitt-middle-school-earns-state-recognition-for-urban-accessibility-effort-with-project-sidewalk/">middle schoolers in Waltham, Massachusetts earning statewide civics recognition</a>.
about.impact.more = Want more? Our sister site <a href="https://accessiblecommunities.org/">accessiblecommunities.org</a> shares news, resources, and guides for putting Project Sidewalk to work in your community.
about.where.title = Where we are
about.where.body = Project Sidewalk is deployed in <span data-live-stat="num_cities">{0}</span> cities across <span data-live-stat="num_countries">{1}</span> countries — and growing. <a href="/cities">See every deployment city</a> or <a href="https://accessiblecommunities.org/use-project-sidewalk/">learn how to bring Project Sidewalk to yours</a>.
about.history.title = Our history
about.history.2012 = Project Sidewalk begins as a research project by Professor Jon E. Froehlich and PhD student Kotaro Hara in the <a href="https://makeabilitylab.cs.washington.edu/">Makeability Lab</a>, with early support from Google and the National Science Foundation.
about.history.2017 = The first city-scale deployment launches in Washington, DC, led by PhD student Manaswi Saha and research scientist Mikey Saugstad, as the lab moves to the University of Washington''s Paul G. Allen School of Computer Science &amp; Engineering.
about.history.2019 = The DC pilot study shows that online crowdsourcing can be used to map an entire city''s sidewalks — and earns a Best Paper Award at CHI 2019.
about.history.2021 = An NSF Smart &amp; Connected Communities grant deepens our partnership with the University of Illinois Chicago and Easterseals, expanding deployments, education programs, and our sister site <a href="https://accessiblecommunities.org/">accessiblecommunities.org</a>.
about.history.today.label = Today
about.history.today = Project Sidewalk operates in <span data-live-stat="num_cities">{0}</span> cities around the world, natively translated into {1} languages and powered by thousands of volunteer mappers.
about.team.title = The team
about.team.intro = Project Sidewalk is university research, led by Professor Jon E. Froehlich at the University of Washington''s <a href="https://makeabilitylab.cs.washington.edu/">Makeability Lab</a> and Professor Yochai Eisenberg at the University of Illinois Chicago, with lead engineering by research scientist Mikey Saugstad — and contributions from more than a hundred students and collaborators over the years.
about.team.current.title = Current team
about.team.past.title = Past leadership
about.team.past.kotarohara = Started Project Sidewalk with Professor Froehlich as his PhD student, pioneering the crowdsourcing and computer-vision methods behind the project — the subject of his <a href="https://makeabilitylab.cs.washington.edu/media/publications/Hara_ScalableMethodsToCollectAndVisualizeSidewalkAccessibilityDataForPeopleWithMobilityImpairments_UMDCSPhDDissertation2016.pdf">dissertation</a>.
about.team.past.davidjacobs = Co-PI on the original NSF grant and the initial Google Faculty Research Award that launched Project Sidewalk, guiding its early computer-vision research.
about.team.past.manaswisaha = Helped lead the first wide-scale deployment in Washington, DC and designed tools for understanding urban accessibility data — the subject of her <a href="https://makeabilitylab.cs.washington.edu/media/publications/Saha_DesigningInteractiveDataDrivenToolsForUnderstandingUrbanAccessibilityAtScale_UWCSPhDDissertation2022.pdf">dissertation</a>.
about.team.contributors.title = Contributors
about.team.contributors.intro = More than 100 high school and undergraduate students have contributed code, designs, and ideas to Project Sidewalk. Part of our mission is to help computer science and design students work on societally impactful projects through experiential learning.
about.team.contributors = … plus community partners and thousands of volunteer mappers around the world — see the <a href="https://makeabilitylab.cs.washington.edu/project/sidewalk/">full project page</a> for more.
about.pubs.title = Related publications
about.pubs.intro = Project Sidewalk research is published at leading human–computer interaction and accessibility venues. If you use our data or tools in your research, please cite our <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3290605.3300292">CHI 2019 paper</a>.
about.pubs.fallback = Browse <a href="https://makeabilitylab.cs.washington.edu/project/sidewalk/">all Project Sidewalk publications</a> on the Makeability Lab website.
about.pubs.showAll = Show all {0} publications
about.data.title = Open data &amp; open source
about.data.body = Everything we collect is open. Download raw labels, label clusters, streets, and accessibility scores through our <a href="/api">public APIs</a>, in formats from CSV to GeoJSON — all published under CC0; see the <a href="/api">API documentation</a> for details and citation guidance. Our <a href="https://github.com/ProjectSidewalk/SidewalkWebpage">code is open source</a>, too.
about.partners.title = Community partners
about.partners.body = We work hand in hand with disability advocacy organizations, governments, schools, and community groups around the world — including Easterseals, World Enabled, Liga Peatonal, and the Active Transportation Alliance — to plan deployments, run community mapping events, and turn data into local action.
about.partners.schools = Educators bring Project Sidewalk into civics and data-science classrooms, and our team and partners have piloted service-learning and workforce-development curricula for youth with disabilities. <a href="https://accessiblecommunities.org/use-project-sidewalk/">Learn how to use Project Sidewalk in your community</a>.
about.funding.title = Funders
about.funding.body = Project Sidewalk is grant-funded academic research, supported by the National Science Foundation with additional support from Google, the Alfred P. Sloan Foundation, PacTrans, and the UW Center for Research and Education on Accessible Technology and Experiences (CREATE).
about.cta.title = Help us map every sidewalk
about.cta.city = Bring Project Sidewalk to your city
about.contact.body = Questions, ideas, or press inquiries? Email us at <a href="mailto:sidewalk@cs.uw.edu">sidewalk@cs.uw.edu</a>, open an issue on <a href="https://github.com/ProjectSidewalk/SidewalkWebpage">GitHub</a>, or follow us on <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/project-sidewalk/">LinkedIn</a> and <a href="https://bsky.app/profile/projectsidewalk.bsky.social">Bluesky</a>.

